cess as a businesswoman in revolutionary Baltimore was soon eclipsed by the rise of a vigorous and often partisan press environment. The revolutionary era also witnessed Baltimore\'s replacement of Annapolis as the center for printing activity in Maryland.',16),(3630,'Williams, Harold A.','<em>The Baltimore Sun, 1837-1987.</em> Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press, 1987.','Harold Williams had the daunting task up updating the celebrated 1937 history of the Sunpapers written by Gerald Johnson, Frank Kent, Hamilton Owens and H. L. Mencken. As a long-time writer and editor for the <em>Sun</em> , Williams tells the story of the one daily paper to survive in the highly competitive Baltimore market littered with names like the <em>Herald</em> , <em>Star</em> , <em>Post</em> , <em>News</em> , <em>American</em> and many others. That this history was written on the eve of the <em>Sun\'s</em> takeover by the Times Mirror Corporation makes this a somewhat bittersweet tale.',NULL),(3631,'Williams, Harold A.','\"HLM and the Great Fire.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 102 (Summer 1987): 2-8.',NULL,NULL),(3632,'Williams, Harold A.','\"Light for All: Arunah S. Abell and the Rise of the Baltimore <em>Sun.</em> \" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 82 (Fall 1987): 197-213.',NULL,16),(3633,'Williams, Harry McKinley.','\"Why George Schuyler Disliked The Sobriquet \'The Negro\'s Mencken:\' A Note on \'Racial\' Sensitivity.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 130 (Summer 1994): 5-9.',NULL,16),(3634,'Williams, Richard Rene.','\"The Fourth Point: Representation of Nineteenth-Century Electromagnetic Phenomena from Edgar Allan Poe to Stephane Mallarme.\" Ph.D. diss., University of Texas, Austin, 1992.',NULL,NULL),(3635,'Wilson, James Southall.','\"Best-sellers in Jefferson\'s Day.\" <em>Virginia Quarterly Review</em> 36 (1960): 222-237.',NULL,16),(3636,'Winchester, Paul, and Frank D. Webb, eds.','<em>Newspapers and Newspaper Men of Maryland Past and Present.</em> Baltimore: Frank L. Silbey & Co. for the Journalists\' Club of Baltimore, 1905.','This venerable survey of Maryland\'s leaders in journalism reminds readers that newspapers were the principal source of information, opinion and entertainment for Marylanders through much of the nineteenth and first half of the twentieth centuries. From vigorously competing dailies in Baltimore to weeklies produced in nearly every county seat, Maryland newspapers employed literary figures as diverse as George Henry Calvert, George Alfred Townsend, Folger McKinsey, Louise Malloy, Frank Kent and H.L. Mencken. This story of those who owned, operated and wrote for these newspapers provides an illuminating look into the tumultuous world of publishing in the Gilded Age.',16),(3637,'Wingate, P. J.','\"H. L. Mencken--Man of Letters.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 90 <em>(</em> Summer 1984): 7-12.',NULL,16),(3638,'Wingate, P. J.','\"Hey Newt: Read More Mencken.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 134 (Summer 1995): 13-14.',NULL,16),(3639,'Wingate, P. J.','\"The Many Mr. Menckens.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 92 (Winter 1984): 8-9.',NULL,16),(3640,'Wingate, P. J.','\"Mencken and Conrad.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 106 (Summer 1988): 5-6.',NULL,16),(3641,'Wingate, P. J.','\"The Mencken-Dreiser Bond.<em>\" Menckeniana</em> 103 (Fall 1987): 6-8.',NULL,16),(3642,'Wingate, P. J.','\"Mencken, Shaw, and Their Two Catholic Sisters.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 124 (Winter 1992): 1-4.',NULL,16),(3643,'Wingate, P. J.','\"Mencken\'s Ghost is Grinning Broadly.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 144 (Winter 1997): 4-5.',NULL,16),(3644,'Wingate, P. J.','\"The Philosophy of H. L. Mencken.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 87 (Fall 1983): 14-16.',NULL,16),(3645,'Wingate, P. J.','\"Women Understood H. L. Mencken.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 128 (Winter 1993): 7-9.',NULL,16),(3646,'Wingate, P. J.','\"Mencken, Shaw and Ebonics.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 141 (Spring 1997): 11-12.',NULL,16),(3647,'Winter, Helmut.','<em>H. L. Mencken: Gesammelte Vorurteile</em> [Collected \'Prejudices\']. Insel Verlag, 2000.',NULL,16),(3648,'