ard C. Papenfuse, 41-62. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press, 1977.',NULL,22),(4367,'Carr, Lois Green.','\"The Foundations of Social Order: Local Government in Colonial Maryland.\" In <em>Town and Country: Essays on the Structure of Local Government in the American Colonies. </em> Edited by Bruce C. Daniels, 72-110. Middletown, CT: Wesleyan University Press, 1978, pp. 72-110.','The structure, powers and functions of local government, which were established in the seventeenth century lasted well into the twentieth century with only slight changes. Based upon English precedents, local power was vested in a system of county courts, and power was not shared with parish vestries until establishment of the Anglican Church in 1692, and even then the vestry never attained the influence it did in Virginia. For most of this time the justices sitting as a group in the county court exercised executive power. During the instability of the Glorious Revolution, the county courts continued to function. Given the high mortality in the seventeenth century, service was not restricted to men who were wealthy or well connected, although that would change in the next century.',NULL),(9406,'Cunningham, Isabel Shipley.','â€œSeparate But Not Equal.â€ <em>Anne Arundel County History Notes</em>, 38 (Fall 2006): 1-2, 7-10.',NULL,NULL),(14427,'Swingle, Anne Bennett.','\"The Battlefield of Disease.\" Johns Hopkins Magazine, 41 (June 1989):40-47, 122','[John Shaw Billings]',NULL),(4370,'Carter, Edward C., II and, Clifford Lewis, III.','\"Sir Edmund Plowden and the New Albion Charter, 1632-1785.\" <em>Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography</em> 83 (1959): 150-179.',NULL,22),(4371,'Cassell, Frank A.','\"General Samuel Smith and the Election of 1800.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 63 (1968): 341-359.',NULL,22),(4372,'Cassell, Frank A.','\"The Great Baltimore Riot of 1812.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 70 (Fall 1975): 241-59.',NULL,22),(4373,'Cassell, Frank A.','<em>Merchant Congressman in the Young Republic: Samuel Smith of Maryland</em>. Madison: The University Press of Wisconsin, 1971.','Samuel Smith epitomizes the history of Baltimore City during the early republic. An officer during the Revolution and the commander of the forces that defended the city against the British attack in 1813, a member of an important merchant family whose economic connections helped him establish a political power base that stretched almost five decades, and sometimes brought him to the brink of economic ruin, he was a major political figure from George Washington\'s presidency through Andrew Jackson\'s. His career also reveals the elusiveness of political labels. As a Republican leader in the 1790s, he opposed the policies of the Federalists and supported those of Thomas Jefferson, but he and his brother Robert Smith had a falling out with James Madison, and by the 1830s he was courted by the more democratic Jacksonians who refused to anoint his kin as party leaders.',NULL),(4374,'Cassell, Frank A.','\"The Structure of Baltimore\'s Politics in the Age of Jefferson, 1795-1812.\" In <em>Law, Society, and Politics in Early Maryland.</em> Edited by Aubrey C. Land, Lois Green Carr, and Edward C. Papenfuse, 277-96. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press, 1977.',NULL,22),(4375,'Catton, Bruce.','\"A Southern Artist on the Civil War.\" <em>American Heritage</em> 9 (1958): 117-120.',NULL,NULL),(4376,'Chase, James S.','\"Genesis of the First National Political Convention: A Case Study in the Development of an American Institution.\" <em>Social Science</em> 50 (1969): 92-115.',NULL,22),(4377,'Chepaitis, Joseph B.','\"Albert C. Ritchie in Power: 1920-1927.\"<em> Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 68 (1973): 383-404.','In fifteen years as governor, Albert C. Ritchie was a popular reformer and one of Maryland\'s foremost governors. The first Maryland governor to succeed himself in office, Ritchie served an unprecedented four terms. Jeffersonian in his adherence to state\'s rights, Ritchie was a progressive who championed an efficient \"business-modeled\" state government, a reduction of taxes and opposed a state Volstead Act.',22),(4378,'Chrismer, James E.','\"Harford County\'s Role in the Development of the Bill of Rights.\" <em>Harford Historical Bulletin</em> 52 (Spring 1992): 33-48.',NULL,22),(4379,'Chused, Richard H.','<em>Private Acts in Public Places: A Social History of Divorce in the Formative Era of American Family Law</em>. Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 1994.',NULL,22),(4380,'Clark, Charles B.','\"The Career of John Seymour, Governor of Maryland, 1704-1709.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 48 (1953): 134-159.',NULL,22),(4381,'Clark, Malcolm C.','\"Federalism at High Tide: the Election of 1796 in Maryland.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 61 (1966): 210-230.',NULL,22),(4382,'Claussen, E. Neal.','\"Hendrick B. Wright and the \'Nocturnal Committee.\'\" <em>Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography</em> 89 (1965): 199-206.',NULL,22),(4383,'Clawson, Frank D.','\"These Men of Maryland Helped Launch Our USA Constitution.\" <em>Cracker Barrel</em> 17 (December 1987): 23-25, 30.',NULL,22),(4384,'Cohen, Richard M., and Jules Witcover.','<em>A Heartbeat Away: The Investigation and Resignation of Vice-President Spiro T. Agnew</em>. New York: Viking, 1974.','A Washington Post Book. The rise and fall of Spiro T. Agnew reflects the seamier side of Maryland politics in the 1960s. Agnew, a former Republican Baltimore County executive and Governor, whose \"law and order\" position during the riots following the assassination of Martin Luther King elevated him from relative obscurity to become Richard Nixon\'s vice-presidential running mate in 1968, emerged as the outspoken domestic policy spokesman for an administration increasingly enmired in the difficulties of extricating the country from the Vietnam war. Prior to assuming federal office, Agnew, like some other Maryland politicians of 