ession Crisis, 1860-1861</em>. Baltimore: Publishing Concepts, 1995.','Asking if Maryland, left to her own devices, would have left the union in 1861, the author asserts that the evidence supports the conclusion that the majority of Marylanders would have preferred to join the Confederacy and many continued to support the southern cause throughout the war. He concludes: \"...the majority of Marylanders were true to their section and state. They supported the South and opposed the North until the overwhelming force of the federal military forced them to cease free and open expression\" (p. 199). Indeed, \"the federal military forced Maryland to stay in the Union\" (p. 203).',22),(4408,'','\"Developments in Maryland Law, 1991-92.\" <em>Maryland Law Review</em> 52, no. 3 (1993): 530-887.',NULL,22),(4409,'','\"Developments in Maryland Law, 1992-93.\" <em>Maryland Law Review</em> 53, no. 3 (1994): 616-1040.',NULL,22),(4410,'Dinkin, Robert J.','\"Elections in Proprietary Maryland.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 73 (June 1978): 129-36.',NULL,22),(4411,'Dinkin, Robert J.','<em> Voting in Provincial America: A Study of Elections in the Thirteen Colonies</em> <em>1689-1776,</em> Contributions in American History, no. 64. Westport, CT: Greenwood Press, 1977.','References to Maryland.',22),(4412,'','\"Divorce in Maryland.\" <em>Newsletter of the Maryland Archives</em> 1 (October 1984): 7.',NULL,22),(4413,'Douglass, John E.','\"Between Pettifoggers and Professionals: Pleaders and Practitioners and the Beginnings of the Legal Profession in Colonial Maryland, 1634-1731.\" <em>American Journal of Legal History</em> 39 (July 1995): 359-84.',NULL,22),(4414,'Dunham, Chester Gray.','\"A Nineteenth Century Baltimore Diplomat: Christopher Hughes Goes to Sweden.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 72 (Fall 1977): 387-400.',NULL,22),(4415,'Durr, Kenneth D.','\"\'Why We Are Troubled:\' White Working-Class Politics in Baltimore, 1940-1980.\" Ph.D. diss., American University, 199