 member Senate, until the electors agreed to reform. Because the Governor was elected by the joint ballot of the legislature, the threat was real. The Nineteen Recalcitrant Van Buren Electors had not anticipated Governor Thomas W. Veazey\'s reaction. Unburdened by express constitutional authority, he nonetheless recalled the former Senate so that a new government could be formed. This broke the back of the boycott and the new legislature created two new counties on the Western Shore, thus increasing its representation in the assembly.',22),(4473,'Hall, Arthur Pendleton, II.','\"State-Issued Bills of Credit and the United States Constitution: The Political Economy of Paper Money in Maryland, New York, Pennsylvania, and South Carolina, 1780-1789.\" Ph.D. diss., University of Georgia, 1991.',NULL,22),(4474,'Haller, Mark H.','\"The Rise of the Jackson Party in Maryland, 1820-1829.\" <em>Journal of Southern History</em> 28 (1962): 307-326.','Against the image that the Jacksonian political movement smashed the existing corrupt system, introducing new leaders and a new agenda in 1828, this study argues that, in Maryland at least, its success was due to a group of politicians, whose institutional support had vanished with the disintegration of the first party system in the 1820s, seeking to capitalize on Old Hickory\'s popularity with the voters in order to return to power. Former Federalists, like Roger B. Taney, or Republicans, like Edward Lloyd, joined supporters of John C. Calhoun to endorse Jackson for the Presidency. Given their desperate backgrounds, and their allegiances to various national leaders, it is not surprising that the Maryland Jacksonian party was unstable and prone to division.',22),(4475,'Hallion, Marie.','\"Criminal Justice in the Province of Maryland.\" <em>The Maryland Historian</em> 15 (Spring/Summer 1984): 3-18.',NULL,22),(4476,'Hanley, Thomas O\'Brien, S.J.','\"The Catholic and Anglican Gentry in Maryland Politics.\"<em> Historical Magazine of the