gton, and an accomplished legal mind who is remembered more for his overbearing judicial manner than his contribution to the law, Samuel Chase\'s life was anything but dull. Indeed, his life reflects many of the conflicting cross-currents between the principles of republicanism and democracy, of judicial responsibility and judicial activism, and the role of the elite in America between the Revolution and the War of 1812.',22),(4485,'Hays, Anne M.','\"Chestertown\'s Tea Party.\" <em>Chesapeake Bay Magazine</em> 6 (May 1976): 15-16.',NULL,22),(4487,'Henig, Gerald S.','\"Henry Winter Davis and the Speakership Contest of 1859-1860.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 68 (1973): 1-19.',NULL,NULL),(4488,'Henry, Milton Lyman, Jr.','\"Henry Winter Davis: Border State Radical.\" (Volumes I and II) Ph.D. diss., Louisiana State University and Agricultural and Mechanical College, 1974.',NULL,22),(4489,'Hickey, Donald R.','\"The Darker Side of Democracy: The Baltimore Riots of 1812.\" <em>Maryland Historian</em> 7 (Fall 1976): 1-19.',NULL,22),(4490,'Hickey, Donald R.','<em>The War of 1812: A Forgotten Conflict</em>. Urbana: University of Illinois Press, 1989.','A comprehensive examination of the political background, military operations, and diplomatic closure of \"Mr. Madison\'s War.\" It may have been forgotten in other areas, but for Maryland the War of 1812 was all too real. The Royal Navy roamed the Chesapeake with impunity, occupied Tangier Island, burned Frenchtown, attacked St. Michaels and Havre de Grace, sacked the nation\'s capitol after defeating the militia at Bladensburg, before meeting defeat after a combined sea-land attack on Baltimore City, which was immortalized in Francis Scott Key\'s \"Star Spangled Banner.\" There is also a chapter on the infamous Baltimore riot of 1812.',NULL),(4491,'Hienton, Louise J.','\"The Hundreds of Prince George\'s County.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 65 (1970): 55-67.',NULL,22),(4492,'','<em>Histories of the Bench an