 entitled, <em>Commentaries on the Constitution</em> dating from February 1787 through September 1788, <em> </em> in which there are references of Maryland; and a final volume will cover the Bill of Rights. Both Federalist and Anti-Federalist material are presented. Unfortunately, the Maryland state volume has yet to be published.',22),(4513,'Jensen, Merrill, et al., ed.','<em>The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections, 1788-1790.</em> 4 volumes. Madison: State Historical Society of Wisconsin, 1976-1989. 4 volumes.','As partisans recognized at the time, the fate of the new federal system was not settled by ratification of the Constitution because the first federal Congress would organize the new government. Therefore a great deal of effort was put into how the congressional and presidential elector districts were organized in each state, not all of which did it the same way, and into the ensuing elections. No Federalist expected that an Anti-Federalist would do a proper job and the Anti-Federalists recognized that it was their last chance to diminish the energy of the new government.. The material for Maryland is contained in volume II.',22),(4514,'Johnson, Herbert A.','\"Chief Justice John Marshall (1801-1835).\" <em>Journal of Supreme Court History</em> (1998): 3-20.',NULL,22),(4515,'Johnstone, Gene.','\"How a Kent County Senator Saved Andrew Johnson\'s Presidency.\" <em>Old Kent</em> 16 (Spring 1999): 3.',NULL,NULL),(4516,'Jonas, Manfred.','\"The Claiborne-Calvert Controversy: an Episode in the Colonization of North America.\" <em>Jahrbuch für Amerikastudien</em> West Germany 11 (1966): 241-250.',NULL,22),(4517,'Jordan, David W.','\"Elections and Voting in Early Colonial Maryland.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 77 (Fall 1982): 238-65.',NULL,22),(4519,'Jordan, David W.','\"\'God\'s Candle\' Within Government: Quakers and Politics in Early Maryland.\" <em>William and Mary Quarterly</em> 3d series, 39 (October 1982): 628-54.',NULL,22),(4520,'Jordan, David W.','\"John Coode, Perennial Rebel.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 70 (Spring 1975): 1-28.','A biography of John Coode, for whom any cause became an unrestrained assault on his opponents, and who became a Protestant scourge to the Catholic establishment in the late seventeenth century. His contradictory career is chronicled and typified by his perennial resistance to authority.',22),(4521,'Jordan, David W.','\"Maryland\'s Privy Council, 1637-1715.\" In<em> Law, Society, and Politics in Early</em> <em>Maryland.</em> Edited by Aubrey C. Land, Lois Green Carr, and Edward C. Papenfuse, 65-87. Baltimore: Johns Hopkins University Press, 1977.',NULL,22),(4522,'Jordan, David W.','\"Political Stability and the Emergence of a Native Elite in Maryland.\" In <em>The Chesapeake in the Seventeenth Century: Essays in Anglo-American Society.</em> Edited by Thad W. Tate and David L. Ammerman, 243-73. Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press, 1979.',NULL,NULL),(4523,'Jordan, David W.','\"Sir Thomas Lawrence, Secretary of Maryland: A Royal Placeman\'s Fortunes in America.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 76 (Spring 1981): 22-44.',NULL,22),(4524,'','\"Judges of the 4th Judicial Circuit of Maryland.\" <em>Glades Star</em> 7 (September 1992): 70, 84.',NULL,22),(4525,'Kelbaugh, Jack.','\"Annapolis 300 Law Enforcement History.\" <em>Anne Arundel County History Notes</em> 26 (January 1995): 8.',NULL,22),(4526,'Kelbaugh, Jack.','\"A Tale of the Whip.\" <em>Anne Arundel County History Notes</em> 30 (October 1998): 18-19.',NULL,22),(4527,'Kennedy, Padraic M.','\"Vista Volunteers Bring about Successful Bail Reform Project in Baltimore.\" <em>American Bar Association Journal</em> 54 (1968): 1093-1096.',NULL,22),(4528,'Kimberly, Charles Michael.','\"The Depression and New Deal in Maryland.\" Ph.D. diss., American University, 1974.',NULL,22),(4529,'Kimberly, Charles M.','\"The Depression in Maryland: The Failure of Voluntaryism.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 70 (Summer 1975): 189-202.','At both the state and local levels, Maryland\'s governmental officials, especially Governor Albert C. Ritchie, failed to offer Depression relief, relying instead on private charities. Ritchie\'s ultimate decision to turn to the federal government was made with reluctance as Voluntaryism proved inadequate to need.',22),(15022,'Raum, Elizabeth. ','<em>The Star Spangled Banner in Translation: What It Really Means</em>. \r\nMankato, MN: Capstone Press, 2009.\r\n\r\n',NULL,NULL),(15004,'Blackpool, Stephen.','<em>Maryland Historical Markers: Allegany & Garrett Counties</em>. Baltimore: Stephen Blackpool, 2004.',NULL,NULL),(4531,'Klingelhofer, Herbert E.','\"The Cautious Revolution: Maryland and the Movement Toward Independence: 1774-1776.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 60 (1965): 261-313.',NULL,22),(4532,'Klingelhofer, Herbert E.','\"Matthew Ridley\'s Diary During the Peace Negotiations of 1782.\" <em>William and Mary Quarterly</em> 20 (1963): 95-133.',NULL,22),(4533,'Knott, Harry C.','\"Two Hangings in St. Mary\'s County, Maryland.\"<em> Chronicles of St. Mary\'s</em> 41 (Summer 1993): 213-17.',NULL,22),(4534,'Krugler, John D.','\"\'Our Trusty and Wellbeloved Councillor:\' The Parliamentary Career of Sir George Calvert, 1609-24.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 72 (Winter 1977): 470-91.',NULL,22),(4535,'Krugler, John D.','\"Sir George Calvert\'s Resignation as Secretary of State and the Founding of Maryland.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 68 (1973): 239-254.',NULL,22),(4536,'Kuehl, John W.','\"The XYZ Affair and American Nationalism: Republican Victories in the Middle Atlantic States.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 67 (1972): 1-20.',NULL,22),(4537,'Lamb, Karl A.','<em>Reasonable Disagreement; Two U.S. Senators and the Choices They Make</em>. New York: Garland, 1998.',NULL,22),(4538,'Lambert, John R., Jr.','\"The Autobiographical Writings of Senator Arthur Pue Gorman.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 58 (1963): 93-122, 233-246.',NULL,22),(4539,'Landon, Alf M.','\"HLM and AML: The 1936 Campaign.\" <em>Menckeniana</em> 75 (Fall 1980): 47-49.',NULL,22),(4540,'Leder, Lawrence H.','\"The Glorious Revolution and the Pattern of Imperial Relationships.\"<em> New York History</em> 46 (1965): 203-211.',NULL,22),(4541,'Lee, J. B.','\"Lessons in Humility: The Revolutionary Transformation of the Governing Elite of Charles County, Maryland.\" In <em>The Transforming Hand of Revolution</em>. Charlottesville: Published for the United States Capitol Historical Society by the University Press of Virginia, 1996.',NULL,22),(4542,'Lee, Jean Buttenhoff.','\"Maryland\'s \'Dangerous Insurrection\' of 1786.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 85 (Winter 1990): 328-44.',NULL,22),(4543,'Lee, Jean B.','<em>The Price of Nationhood: The American Revolution in Charles County</em>. New York: W. W. Norton & Co., 1994.','This intensive and insightful study of a single county offers insight into several large themes in Maryland history - \"the American Revolution as a transforming, ongoing phenomenon, civilian\'s responses to the War for Independence, the tenor of the nation\'s formative years, and the nature of Chesapeake society.\" During this period Charles Country changed from prosperous economy, securely connected to the outside world through overseas trade, into a stagnant backwater, whose forward looking population searched for opportunity elsewhere. Unlike other areas of Maryland, where the Revolutionary years were tumultuous, there were few challenges to the status quo. Cut off from the empire, entrepreneurial whites left the county in search of wealth and opportunity, often as close as Washington, DC, and the population became overwhelmingly unfree.',22),(4544,'LeFurgy, William G.','\"Baltimore\'s Wards, 1797-1978: A Guide.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine </em> 75 (June 1980): 145-53.','An especially useful guide to the laws which created the Baltimore City wards, and the maps