ithin and between parties during this period, this interpretation focuses on his emergence as a state\'s rights advocate over his four terms as Governor. True to his Progressive background, his early emphasis as Governor was administrative reform, such as a State Merit System and a comprehensive administrative reorganization. He emerged as an opponent to Prohibition, successfully opposing state legislation to enforce the Volsted Act, and as a critic of the Ku Klux Klan. He became as a contender for the Democratic presidential nomination between 1924 and 1932, emphasizing a state\'s rights position, but his refusal to co-operate with the New Deal and his inability to deal with the economic and social devastation of the depression in Maryland undermined any hope for re-election to a fifth term in 1934.',NULL),(4551,'Levin, James.','\"Governor Albert C. Ritchie and the Democratic Convention of 1932.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 67 (1972): 278-293.',NULL,22),(4552,'Levin, James.','\"Governor Albert Ritchie and the Democratic National Convention of 1924.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 66 (1971): 101-120.',NULL,22),(4553,'Levine, Marc V.','\"Standing Political Decisions and Critical Realignment: The Pattern of Maryland Politics, 1872-1948.\" <em>Journal of Politics</em> 38 (May 1976): 292-325.',NULL,22),(4554,'Levy, Daniel S.','\"The Life Expectancies of Colonial Maryland Legislators.\" <em>Historical Methods </em> 20 (Winter 1987): 17-27.',NULL,22),(4555,'Lewis, Walker.','<em>Without Fear or Favor: A Biography of Chief Justice Roger Brooke Taney</em>. Boston: Houghton Mifflin Company, 1965.','Roger B. Taney, remembered for the Dred Scott decision and his efforts to challenge President Abraham Lincoln\'s use of executive power when he suspended <em>habeas corpus</em> early in the Civil War obscure other aspects of his life worth recalling. Originally from Calvert County, he made his mark as an attorney in Fredericktown, where he married into the Key family, before moving to Baltimore City in search of opportunity and fortune in the law. A former Federalist, he quickly emerged as an organizer of the Jacksonian party, and became a close advisor of the president who appointed him to several cabinet posts, before naming him Chief Justice in 1836 following the death of John Marshall. The controversy over the Dred Scott decision (1857), which exacerbated the slavery issue rather than solving it, all but obscures his accomplishments as Chief Justice. The Taney Court was known for its willingness to embrace economic progress and to shed old restrictive judicial norms, which was evident early in his career on the court in the Charles River Bridge decision (1837).',NULL),(4556,'Lewis, H. H. Walker.','\"The Lawyers\' Round Table of Baltimore.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine </em> 70 (Fall 1975): 279-85.',NULL,22),(4557,'Lewis, H. H. Walker.','<em>The Lawyer\'s Round Table of Baltimore and its Charter Members. </em> Baltimore: Maryland Historical Society, 1978.',NULL,22),(4558,'Lewis, H. H. Walker.','<em>The Maryland Constitution 1776.</em> Baltimore: Published by the author, 1976.',NULL,22),(4559,'Lewis, H. H. Walker.','<em>The Rule Day Club: Baltimore Maryland.</em> Baltimore: Maryland Historical Society, 1980.',NULL,22),(4560,'Lewis, H. H. Walker.','<em>The United States District Court of Maryland.</em> Baltimore: Maryland State Bar Association, 1977.',NULL,22),(4561,'Lewis, Lionel S.','<em>The Cold War and Academic Governance: The Lattimore Case at Johns Hopkins</em>. Albany: State University of New York Press, 1993.',NULL,22),(4562,'Liebmann, George W.','<em>Maryland Practice: District Court Law and Practice.</em> 2 vols. St. Paul, MN: West Publishing Co., 1976.','Contains historical background.',22),(4563,'Littlefield, Douglas R.','\"Maryland Sectionalism and the Development of the Potomac Route to the West.\" <em>The Maryland Historian</em> 14 (Fall/Winter 1983): 31-52.',NULL,22),(4564,'Locke, Diana.','\"Oyster Fis