constitutions (1776, 1851, 1864, 1867), the author studies trends in civil rights and liberties, privacy and personal autonomy, criminal law and procedure, economic rights and the revival of substantive due process, and judicial review of separation of powers and state-local issues. He finds that Maryland followed a middle way, in that it was not on the cutting edge of state constitutionalism, nor was it in the van. Some may have looked to state courts to guarantee greater criminal protections than the Supreme Court was willing to recognize in the 1970s, which was the case in Maryland, but the state court also expanded freedom of expression and equality of treatment. At the same time, state courts have recognized less protection than that defined by the Supreme Court in such areas as commercial speech and defamation. The Maryland courts have been unwilling to look to state law first without considering developments in the federal law to find a separate and independent body of law. This might change given the Supreme Court\'s more recent deference to the principles of federalism and the recognition of state\'s rights.',22),(4758,'Tomlinson, Edward A.','\"The Maryland Administrative Procedure Act: Forty Years Old in 1997.\" <em>Maryland Law Review</em> 56, no. 1 (1997): 196-272.',NULL,22),(4759,'Towers, Frank.','\"Violence as a Tool of Party Dominance: Election Riots and the Baltimore Know-Nothings, 1854-1860.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 93 (Spring 1998): 4-37.','The relationship between municipal power and election violence on mid-nineteenth-century Baltimore election returns. Police, gangs, and control of money and arms, which foreshadowed the political machines seen later in the century, influenced these elections as much as did the more conventional categories of analysis--party ideology and voters\' social backgrounds.',22),(4760,'Towers, Frank, ed.','\"Military Waif: A Sidelight on the Baltimore Riot of 19 April 1861.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 89 (Winter 1994): 427-46.',NULL,NULL),(4761,'','\"Transcript of Dr. Thomas Bray\'s Letter to Major Dent, Attorney General of Maryland, Upon Final Passage of The Act of Establishment.\" <em>The Record</em> 57 (October 1992): 1-3.',NULL,22),(4762,'Tushnet, Mark.','<em>Making Civil Rights Law: Thurgood Marshall and the Supreme Court, 1936-61</em>. New York: Oxford University Press, 1994.','Thurgood Marshall, the first African-American to be named to the Supreme Court, built a reputation as a skilled civil rights litigator with the NAACP. In addition to playing a key role in developing and implementing the legal strategy behind the famous <em>Brown v. Board of Education</em> (1954) desegregation case, among other important civil rights cases, he began his career twenty years earlier by successfully challenging the Jim Crow system which excluded blacks from attending the University of Maryland\'s law school. Written by one of his former Supreme Court law clerks, this is a sophisticated and comprehensive examination of the legal aspects of the civil rights movement, covering Marshall\'s career prior to his appointment to the Supreme Court.',22),(4763,'Tyson, Raymond W.','\"Henry Winter Davis: Orator for the Union.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 58 (1963): 1-19.',NULL,22),(4764,'Tyson, Raymond W.','\"A Southerner Who Spoke for the Union.\" <em>Southern Speech Journal</em> 30 (1964): 117-132.',NULL,22),(4765,'Van Ness, James S.','\"On Untying the Knot: The Maryland Legislature and Divorce Petitions.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 67 (1972): 171-175.',NULL,22),(4766,'Verstandig, Lee Lovely.','\"The Emergence of the Two-Party System in Maryland, 1787-1796.\" Ph.D. diss., Brown University, 1970.',NULL,22),(4767,'Virta, Alan.','\"\'Payable Before July 1:\' The County Levy and Levyers.\"<em> News and Notes from the Prince George\'s County Historical Society</em>, 11 (January 1983): 3-6.',NULL,NULL),(4768,'Vivian, Jean H.','\"The Poll Tax Controversy in 