Cavalcade</em> 39 (Autumn 1989): 62-69, 100-5.',NULL,25),(4950,'Click, Patricia Catherine.','<em>The Spirit of the Times: Amusements in Nineteenth Century Baltimore, Norfolk and Richmond.</em> Charlottesville: University Press of Virginia, 1989.','Click examines the evolution of popular amusements and attitudes toward them in Baltimore, Norfolk, and Richmond during the period 1810-1870. The volume considers museum exhibitions, theater, horse racing, clubs, and resorts. She argues that throughout the period there was a broadened acceptance of popular amusements, though the choice of particular entertainment forms often stood as a sign of social status. The study is based upon manuscript sources at the Maryland Historical Society and comparable archives in Virginia, and includes a set of illustrations from those collections.',25),(4951,'Cochran, Sheila.','\"Mount Nebo and the Fletchall Family.\" <em>Montgomery County Story</em> 31 (May 1988): 11-22.',NULL,25),(4952,'Codignola, Luca, and David T. Konig.','<em>Terre d\'America e Burocragie Romana: Simon Stock, Propegande Fide, La Colonia di Lord Baltimore a Terranova, 1621-1649.</em> Venice, Italy: Marsilio, 1982.',NULL,25),(4953,'Coers, D. V.','\"New Light on the Composition of Ebenezer Cook\'s <em>Sot-Weed Factor</em>.\" <em>American Literature</em> 49 (January 1978): 604-06.','Coers offers evidence to support the contention that Ebenezer Cook\'s satire <em>The Sot-Weed Factor</em> was likely written no earlier than 1702, later than the 1695 date previously ascribed. He draws upon internal references in Cook\'s writing to Queen Anne, not crowned monarch until 1702, and a Dorchester County Court land record to support his case. The later date would suggest that the work was based on his visit to Maryland in the 1690s, but not written until afterwards.',NULL),(4954,'Cohen, Blanche Klasmer.','\"Benjamin Klasmer\'s Contribution to Baltimore\'s Musical History.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 72 (Summer 1977): 272-