esapeake region, the structure of living arrangements, and the gendered nature of tasks. The evidence suggests how gendered and class-based activities contributed to both household production and accrued wealth. The authors conclude that comparisons between the three sites provide the basis for understanding how household wealth was a direct corollary of the ability to secure a large work force and to develop a high degree of specialization.',NULL),(5066,'Gibson, Karen Jensen.','<em>Brigade, Seats!: the Naval Academy Cookbook</em>. Revised and updated edition. Annapolis, MD: Naval Institute Press, 1993.',NULL,25),(5067,'Gildea, William.','<em>When the Colts Belonged to Baltimore: A Father and a Son, a Team and a Time</em>. New York: Ticknor & Fields, 1994.',NULL,25),(5068,'Gilje, Paul A.','\"The Baltimore Riots of 1812 and the Breakdown of the Anglo-American Mob Tradition.\" <em>Journal of Social History</em> 13 (Summer 1980): 547-64.',NULL,25),(5069,'Gilje, Paul A.','\"\'Le Menu Peuple\' in America: Identifying the Mob in the Baltimore Riots of 1812.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 81 (Spring 1986): 50-66.','Gilje seeks to determine the social composition of the mobs in the Baltimore riots of 1812-\"the most significant example of urban disorder between the American Revolution and the Age of Jackson.\" Drawing upon evidence from court records, city directories, and state assembly reports for clues on occupation, place of residence, and militia rank, he concludes that mob participants and leaders were drawn from both the middle and working classes, especially from neighborhoods like Fells Point, Old Town, and Federal Hill. However, as the riots intensified and became less controlled, a shift occurred toward a preponderance of working class involvement.',25),(5070,'Gittings, David S.','<em>Maryland and the Thoroughbred.</em> Baltimore: Hoffman Brothers Co., 1932.',NULL,25),(5071,'Glick, Susan.','\"No Small Fetes.\" <em>Maryland</em> 27 (May/June 1995): 12-18,