ess, 1977.',NULL,25),(5245,'Menard, Russell R.','\"Population, Economy, and Society in Seventeenth-Century Maryland.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 79 (Spring 1984): 71- 92.','Menard examines some of the complex social and economic patterns underlying the rapid population growth of Maryland during the seventeenth century despite strong in-migration, high mortality, a shortage of females, and later marriage which often produced unstable family life. Tobacco exports rose dramatically, but the economy eventually suffered from over-dependence on a single crop. Though the colony was established with aristocratic goals, immigrants and their offspring initially created a social and economic pattern in which small planters predominated. However, by the century\'s end a new gentry class clearly had emerged in an order characterized by greater dependence on slave labor, a decline of indentured servitude, and heightened degrees of inequality.',NULL),(5246,'Meneely, Jane.','\"Point of No Return.\" <em>Chesapeake Bay Magazine</em> 29 (October 1999): 100-103.',NULL,25),(5247,'Meyer, Eugene L.','\"Replaying the One-Armed Bandit.\" <em>Chesapeake Country Life</em> 4 (April 1983): 9-11; 23; 37.','Slot machines in Southern Maryland.',25),(5248,'Meyers, Francis J.','\"Wild Dreams and Harsh Realities: Lefty Grove and the Life of Organized Baseball in Allegany County, 1900-1939.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 87 (Summer 1992): 146-57.',NULL,25),(5249,'Micklus, Robert, ed.','<em>The Ancient and Honorable Tuesday Club</em>. Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press, 1990.',NULL,25),(14611,'Devitt, E. I.','\"Letters of Father Joseph Mosley, S.J. and Some Extracts from his Diary (1757-1786).\" <em>Records of the American Catholic Historical Society</em>, 17 (1906): 180-210, 289-311.',NULL,NULL),(5251,'Miller, Fred.','\"Bayside Escapes.\" <em>Chesapeake Bay Magazine</em> 23 (October 1993): 29-33.',NULL,25),(5252,'Miller, Henry Michael.','\"Colonization and Subsistence