aryland Historical Magazine</em> 90 (Winter 1995): 404-23.','Argues that Thomas Sully\'s painting <em>Lady with a Harp: Eliza Ridgely</em> was a propaganda piece to counter the British stereotype of American women as \"being unsophisticated, ignorant, and devoid of social graces\" (406). This portrait of fifteen-year-old Ridgely shows grace, poise, feminity, and other traits (including instrumental music) associated with British of true womanhood.',27),(6080,'Towers, Frank.','\"Race, Power, and Money in Antebellum Baltimore: Mary Ridgely\'s Thousand-Dollar Note.\" <em>Maryland Historical Magazine</em> 88 (Fall 1993): 317-23.',NULL,27),(6081,'Toynbee, Polly.','\"\'Classification\' and \'Adjustment\' in a Maryland Women\'s Prison.\" <em>Washington Monthly</em> 5 (1973): 41-58.',NULL,27),(6082,'Trindal, Elizabeth Steger.','<em>Mary Surratt: An American Tragedy</em>. Gretna, LA: Pelican Publishing Company, Inc., 1996.',NULL,27),(6083,'Verge, Laurie.','\"119 Years Ago-The Spring of 1865.\" <em>Passport to the Past</em> 5 (Spring 1994): 12-14.',NULL,27),(6084,'Virta, Alan.','\"Two Women of Prince George\'s County.\" <em>News and Notes from the Prince George\'s County Historical Society</em>, 21 (October 1993): 3-4.',NULL,NULL),(6085,'','\"Wallis: Duchess of Windsor.\" <em>MHS/News</em> (October-December 1999): 10-11.',NULL,27),(6086,'Walters, R. Eugenia.','\"Some Reminiscences of Miss R. Eugenia Walters.\" <em>News and Notes from the Prince George\'s County Historical Society</em>, 21 (May 1994): [6-10].',NULL,NULL),(6087,'Weaver, Diane E.','\"Maryland Women and the Transformation of Politics, 1890s-1930.\" Ph.D. diss., University of Maryland at College Park, 1992.','Women went from being outsiders to political players by bringing their issues to the attention of local and state government. Working together, women activists and male politicians broadened the responsibility of government and established a public role for women. The suffrage movement in Maryland was an exte